    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-10-26T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-10-26T19:00:00-05:00" n="232"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d232">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/14197: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-10-26T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 26, 1938—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>364. Your 687, October 26, 8 p.m., paragraph 3. You are authorized and instructed
                    to take action similar to that taken by your British colleague but of course
                    avoiding the making of any threat such as appears in the last sentence of his
                    text as quoted in your telegram under reference.<note n="53" xml:id="d232fn53"
                        >For Ambassador Grew’s letter of October 27 to the Japanese Vice Minister
                        for Foreign Affairs, see <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_626">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 626</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated to Shanghai and Chungking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
